A more coarse-grained view of the raw data shows an example of patient adaptation over many steps (Fig. 7, right panel). The figure shows that after P1 walked for about 20 steps without assistance, the trainer began applying small assistive forces, which quickly increased in magnitude over a few steps. In response, P1 showed a small increase in swing height that persisted. In contrast, the changes in swing length were more gradual, more variable, and continued increasing throughout the trial. As the trial progressed, the trainer decreased the anterior assistive force while increasing the vertical force. For illustrative purposes, i.e., to highlight data trends, first-order discrete-time dynamic models (i.e., \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
